{"key":"processedPost-11323352","value":{"id":11323352,"first":11319690,"last":11582391,"when":1256573358,"utime":"10/26/09 07:09 PM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />The idea of \"air\" needing to replace the O2 burned is not true (although it doesn't matter since we're not worried about sterile air).&nbsp; Consuming O2 in the box means that more O2 will flow into the box due to the partial pressure effect.&nbsp; In statistical mechanics this means that since there is a higher concentration of O2 outside than inside it is more likely for an O2 molecule to move in than out.&nbsp; However, the opposite is true for the CO2 and H2O vapor, thereby balancing the pressure.&nbsp; As long as the total number of air molecules in the box doesn't change there is no net negative pressure.</blockquote><br />Irrelevant.<br />The O2 being consumed by the flame must be replaced.&nbsp; Thus there is turbulence and air movement in and out of the box, which is what you don't want. The heat also causes convective turbulence, again stirring the air. Nobody is counting molecules.<br />RR"}}